   <tr><td>\f$E_R\f$</td><td>1/Kelvin</td><td>Respiration temperature response rate.</td></tr>
   <tr><td>\f$k_C\f$</td><td>unitless</td><td>CO<sub>2</sub> response rate.</td></tr>
   </table>

   \subsubsection PhotoLightParam Response of Assimilation Rate to Light

   The response of the assimilation rate to light is obtained from gas exchange measurements at reference temperature (\f$T_{ref}\f$) and CO<sub>2</sub> (\f$C_{i,ref}\f$) in which the irradiance is varied across some range.  However, one important detail is that the dark respiration rate should be removed such that \f$A=0\f$ in the dark (see plot below).  This can be done by measuring the net CO<sub>2</sub> flux starting in the dark, then subtracting the dark flux from the total flux for each subsequent light level.

   \image html images/LightResponse.png

   \subsubsection PhotoTempParam Response of Assimilation Rate to Temperature

   The response of the assimilation rate to temperature is obtained using gas exchange measurements at saturating light levels and the reference CO<sub>2</sub> concentration.  The temperature is varied across some range, and the assimilation rate is measured.  It is assumed that the optimum temperature \f$T_{opt}\f$ is the temperature corresponding to the maximum measured assimilation rate.  The model is fit to the data to determine \f$T_{min}\f$ and \f$q\f$.

   \image html images/TempResponse.png

   \subsubsection PhotoRespParam Response of Respiration Rate to Temperature

   The response of the dark respiration to temperature is obtained using gas exchange measurements in the dark.  The leaf is first acclimated to the dark chamber, then leaf temperature is varied across some range.  The model is then fit to the data to determine parameters.

   \image html images/RespResponse.png

   \subsubsection PhotoCO2Param Response of Assimilation Rate to CO2

   The response of the assimilation rate is obtained using gas exchange measurements at saturating light levels and the reference temperature \f$T_{ref}\f$, but with varying external CO<sub>2</sub> concentration (which produces varying intercellular CO<sub>2</sub>).

   \image html images/CO2Response.png


 \section PhotoC4Model C4 Photosynthesis Model (von Caemmerer, 2021)

 The plug-in also provides an implementation of the updated steady-state C4 photosynthesis model of <a href="https://doi.org/10.1093/jxb/erab266">von Caemmerer (2021)</a> (<em>Journal of Experimental Botany</em> 72:6003-6017), intended for C4 crop species (maize, sorghum, sugarcane, millet, switchgrass, etc.). The model couples PEP carboxylation (Vpmax / Kp) in the mesophyll with Rubisco fixation (Vcmax) in the bundle sheath, plus an electron-transport-limited rate. Net assimilation is \f$A = \min(A_c, A_j)\f$ where \f$A_c\f$ is the enzyme-limited rate and \f$A_j\f$ is the electron-transport-limited rate. Both are solutions of quadratic equations in A derived from steady-state balance between the C4 cycle, CO<sub>2</sub> leakage from the bundle sheath, and photorespiration.

 Users enable the C4 model by calling \ref PhotosynthesisModel::setModelType_C4() followed by \ref PhotosynthesisModel::setModelCoefficients(const C4ModelCoefficients&) with a configured \ref C4ModelCoefficients struct. Default parameters correspond to <em>Setaria viridis</em> (NADP-ME subtype) per Table 1 of the paper.

 \subsection PhotoC4Equations Model Equations

 Symbols used: \f$C_m\f$ = mesophyll cytosolic CO<sub>2</sub> partial pressure (\f$\mu\f$bar); \f$C_i\f$ = intercellular CO<sub>2</sub> (\f$\mu\f$mol/mol ≡ \f$\mu\f$bar at 1 atm); \f$O_m\f$ = mesophyll O<sub>2</sub> (\f$\mu\f$bar); \f$V_{c,max}\f$, \f$V_{p,max}\f$, \f$J_{max}\f$ = maximum Rubisco / PEPC / electron-transport rates; \f$K_c, K_o, K_p\f$ = Michaelis constants for Rubisco (CO<sub>2</sub> and O<sub>2</sub>) and PEPC; \f$\gamma^* = 0.5 / S_{Rubisco}\f$; \f$g_m\f$ = mesophyll conductance; \f$g_{bs}\f$ = bundle-sheath conductance; \f$\alpha\f$ = fraction of PSII in the bundle sheath; \f$a_o\f$ = O<sub>2</sub>/CO<sub>2</sub> solubility–diffusivity ratio; \f$R_d\f$ = total leaf mitochondrial respiration; \f$R_m = R_{m,frac}\cdot R_d\f$ = mesophyll share of \f$R_d\f$; \f$x\f$ = fraction of linear electron transport partitioned to the mesophyll; \f$f_{cyc}\f$ = fraction of cyclic electron flow; \f$h\f$ = protons per ATP (= 4); \f$\theta\f$ = curvature of the J response; \f$f\f$ = spectral-quality correction; \f$V_{pr}\f$ = PEP regeneration cap.

 \subsubsection PhotoC4CmCi Coupling between Ci and Cm (paper Eq. 50)

 \f$C_m = C_i - A / g_m\f$

 For a prescribed \f$C_i\f$ (supplied by the stomatal-conductance balance), the plug-in solves for \f$C_m\f$ by damped fixed-point iteration: starting from \f$C_m^{(0)} = C_i\f$, at each step compute \f$A(C_m)\f$ and update \f$C_m^{(k+1)} = 0.5\,C_m^{(k)} + 0.5\,(C_i - A / g_m)\f$ until convergence. When \f$C_m\f$ is supplied directly via \ref PhotosynthesisModel::setCm() (e.g., for spreadsheet validation) this iteration is skipped.

 \subsubsection PhotoC4PEP PEP carboxylation (paper Eq. 19)

 \f$V_p = \min\!\left(\dfrac{C_m V_{p,max}}{C_m + K_p},\ V_{pr}\right)\f$

 \subsubsection PhotoC4ElectronTransport Electron transport capacity (paper Eqs. 31, 34, 35)

 Incident PAR is converted to the PSII-absorbed rate \f$I_2 = I\cdot\mathrm{absorptance}\cdot\rho\cdot(1-f)\f$, with \f$\rho = (1 - f_{cyc}) / (2 - f_{cyc})\f$. The whole-chain linear electron-transport rate J is the smaller root of the non-rectangular hyperbola

 \f$\theta J^2 - (I_2 + J_{max})\,J + I_2\,J_{max} = 0,\qquad J = \dfrac{(I_2 + J_{max}) - \sqrt{(I_2 + J_{max})^2 - 4\theta I_2 J_{max}}}{2\theta}\f$

 The ATP/electron stoichiometry is \f$z = (3 - f_{cyc}) / (h\,(1 - f_{cyc)})\f$. ATP is partitioned between mesophyll and bundle sheath by \f$x\f$, giving \f$J_m = x J\f$ and \f$J_{bs} = (1-x) J\f$.

 \subsubsection PhotoC4Ac Enzyme-limited rate (quadratic in A; paper Eqs. 20–24 + g_bs terms per reference spreadsheet)

 \f$a_c A^2 + b_c A + c_c = 0\f$, with the smaller root \f$A_c = (-b_c - \sqrt{b_c^2 - 4 a_c c_c})/(2 a_c)\f$:

 \f$a_c = 1 - \alpha K_c / (a_o K_o)\f$

 \f$b_c = -\left[(V_p - R_m + g_{bs} C_m) + (V_{c,max} - R_d) + g_{bs} K_c (1 + O_m/K_o) + (\alpha/a_o)(\gamma^* V_{c,max} + R_d K_c / K_o)\right]\f$

 \f$c_c = (V_{c,max} - R_d)(V_p - R_m + g_{bs} C_m) - g_{bs}\left[V_{c,max}\,\gamma^* O_m + R_d K_c (1 + O_m/K_o)\right]\f$

 \subsubsection PhotoC4Aj Electron-transport-limited rate (quadratic in A; paper Eqs. 39–43)

 \f$a_j A^2 + b_j A + c_j = 0\f$, with smaller root \f$A_j = (-b_j - \sqrt{b_j^2 - 4 a_j c_j})/(2 a_j)\f$:

 \f$a_j = 1 - 7 \gamma^* \alpha / (3 a_o)\f$

 \f$b_j = -\left[(J_m z / 2 - R_m + g_{bs} C_m) + (J_{bs} z / 3 - R_d) + g_{bs}\,7 \gamma^* O_m / 3 + (\alpha \gamma^*/a_o)\,(J_{bs} z / 3 + 7 R_d / 3)\right]\f$

 \f$c_j = (J_m z / 2 - R_m + g_{bs} C_m)\,(J_{bs} z / 3 - R_d) - g_{bs}\,\gamma^* O_m\,(J_{bs} z / 3 + 7 R_d / 3)\f$

 \subsubsection PhotoC4Net Net assimilation (paper Eq. 45)

 \f$A = \min(A_c, A_j)\f$

 \subsubsection PhotoC4Temp Temperature responses

 All of \f$V_{p,max}, V_{c,max}, J_{max}, R_d, g_m\f$ use the same peaked-Arrhenius framework as the C3 Farquhar model (\ref PhotosyntheticTemperatureResponseParameters), with four setter overloads per parameter (constant / monotonic Arrhenius / peaked with default dHd / peaked with explicit dHd). The kinetic constants \f$K_c, K_o, K_p, \gamma^*\f$ use simple Arrhenius \f$K(T) = K_{25}\cdot\exp[\Delta H\cdot((1/298.15 - 1/T)/R)]\f$ — not user-settable via overloads, but the struct fields can be edited directly. The paper's Jmax Gaussian response \f$J_{max}(T) = J_{max}(T_o)\exp(-((T - T_o)/\Omega)^2)\f$ is approximated by peaked Arrhenius; at 25 °C the default \f$J_{max} = 247.69\f$ matches the Gaussian exactly, with peaked-Arrhenius parameters chosen to approximate the Gaussian elsewhere.

 \subsection PhotoC4Usage Example: running the C4 model

 ~~~~~~~~{.cpp}
 PhotosynthesisModel photomodel(&context);
 C4ModelCoefficients c4;
 c4.setVpmax(200.f, 50.1f);           // Vpmax = 200 μmol/m²/s at 25 °C with Arrhenius E = 50.1 kJ/mol
 c4.setVcmax(40.f, 78.0f);            // Vcmax = 40 μmol/m²/s at 25 °C, Ea = 78 kJ/mol
 c4.setJmax(247.7f, 77.9f, 43.f, 260.f);  // Peaked Arrhenius (Topt = 43 °C)
 c4.setRd(1.f, 66.4f);
 c4.setMesophyllConductance_gm(1.0f, 49.8f);   // gm = 1 mol/m²/s/bar at 25 °C
 photomodel.setModelCoefficients(c4);
 photomodel.optionalOutputPrimitiveData("Cm");
 photomodel.optionalOutputPrimitiveData("Vp");
 photomodel.run();
 ~~~~~~~~

