 \subsection PhotoC4Library C4 Species Parameter Library

 Helios ships a small library of published C4 parameter sets accessible through \ref PhotosynthesisModel::getC4CoefficientsFromLibrary and \ref PhotosynthesisModel::setC4CoefficientsFromLibrary. Each library entry specifies <em>every</em> parameter the model reads — including the "complementary" kinetic constants (\f$K_c\f$, \f$K_o\f$, \f$K_p\f$) and scalar structural parameters that the source paper held fixed while fitting the headline rate constants. Mixing the headline values from one entry with the fixed-parameter assumptions of another will produce biased predictions, so treat each entry as atomic. Unknown species keys raise \c helios_runtime_error; key matching is case-insensitive.

 <table>
 <tr><th>Species key</th><th>Subtype</th><th>Vcmax(25)<br/>μmol/m²/s</th><th>Vpmax(25)<br/>μmol/m²/s</th><th>Jmax(25)<br/>μmol/m²/s</th><th>Rd(25)<br/>μmol/m²/s</th><th>gm(25)<br/>mol/m²/s/bar</th><th>Kc(25)<br/>μbar</th><th>Ko(25)<br/>μbar</th><th>Kp(25)<br/>μbar</th><th>fcyc</th><th>T-response</th><th>Source</th></tr>
 <tr><td>SetariaViridis_vC2021</td><td>NADP-ME</td><td>40</td><td>200</td><td>247.69</td><td>0.4</td><td>1.0</td><td>1210</td><td>292000</td><td>82</td><td>0.3</td><td>Arrhenius (Jmax peaked)</td><td>von Caemmerer (2021) Table 1; kinetics Boyd <em>et al.</em> (2015); gm Ubierna <em>et al.</em> (2017).</td></tr>
 <tr><td>GenericC4_vC2000</td><td>NADP-ME</td><td>60</td><td>120</td><td>400</td><td>1.0</td><td>∞ (10<sup>4</sup>)</td><td>1210</td><td>292000</td><td>80</td><td>0</td><td>Q10=2.3 → Arrhenius Ea≈61.6</td><td>von Caemmerer (2000) <em>Biochemical Models of Leaf Photosynthesis</em>; plantecophys AciC4 defaults.</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Maize_Massad2007</td><td>NADP-ME</td><td>60</td><td>120</td><td>400</td><td>0.6</td><td>∞ (10<sup>4</sup>)</td><td>650</td><td>450000</td><td>80</td><td>0</td><td>Peaked Arrhenius</td><td>Massad <em>et al.</em> (2007) <em>Plant Cell Environ.</em> 30:1191 (T-responses); plantecophys defaults at 25 °C.</td></tr>
 </table>

 Entry-specific caveats:
 - <b>SetariaViridis_vC2021</b> — the C4 struct's default constructor also carries this parameterization, except \f$R_d\f$: the library entry uses \f$R_d = 0.01 \cdot V_{cmax} = 0.4\f$ μmol/m²/s per the original paper's convention, while the struct constructor sets \f$R_d = 1.0\f$ for historical compatibility.
 - <b>GenericC4_vC2000</b> — the original parameterization uses Q10 temperature responses. Helios approximates these with Arrhenius (\f$E_a = R \cdot T_{\mathrm{ref}}^2 \cdot \ln(Q_{10})/10\f$ with \f$T_{\mathrm{ref}} = 298.15\f$ K), which matches Q10 behavior within ~1% over 15–40 °C. \f$f_{cyc}=0\f$ recovers the linear-electron-flow ATP stoichiometry of the original vC2000 model.
 - <b>Maize_Massad2007</b> — Massad fitted the headline rate constants against Bernacchi (2001) C3-derived \f$K_c\f$ and \f$K_o\f$ (much smaller than the Boyd 2015 C4 values used for Setaria). <b>Do not substitute Setaria's \f$K_c/K_o\f$ into this entry</b> — the \f$V_{cmax}\f$ value is only internally consistent with the Bernacchi values. The paper assumed infinite mesophyll conductance, so the entry sets \f$g_m = 10^4\f$ mol/m²/s/bar as an effectively infinite value. The \f$K_p\f$ temperature response in this entry is taken from Boyd (2015) rather than Massad's own Q10=2.1, since Massad's value is known to overestimate \f$K_p\f$ temperature sensitivity. The 0.6 μmol/m²/s default for \f$R_d\f$ is a library convention (0.01·\f$V_{cmax}\f$) — Massad themselves used \f$R_d = 0\f$ for their final fits and reported results as insensitive to the \f$R_d\f$ choice.

 \note The C4 model's \ref C4ModelCoefficients struct defaults match the paper's Table 1 for <em>Setaria viridis</em>. Two implementation notes distinguish Helios from the paper's supplementary spreadsheet: (1) the Jmax temperature response uses peaked Arrhenius (same API as C3) rather than the paper's Gaussian — Jmax(25 °C) = 247.69 matches the Gaussian at 25 °C; users who need exact Gaussian behavior at other temperatures should fit peaked-Arrhenius parameters or set Jmax as a constant. (2) The Vpr cap in Eq. 19 is always applied; the paper's spreadsheet omits it, so Helios gives slightly lower A at high C_m when V_p,MM > V_pr.

 C4-specific optional output primitive data (\c Cm, \c Vp, plus C4-specific semantics for \c limitation_state) are listed in the \ref PhotoOptionalOutputData section near the top of this page.

*/
